<FIRST>r a PM-AliensDefense 1stLd-Writethru a0495 12-20 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aliens Defense, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illegal Immigrants Fighting U.S. Government With Fifth Amendment
Cudgel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to RAISE legal argument; PICKS UP 17th graf
pvs, `One of ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight Latin American stablehands seized at
a racetrack a year ago have taken the Fifth Amendment, challenging
the government to prove they are illegal aliens. The government
says it doesn't have to to deport them.
   While illegal immigrants often don't know their rights and
prefer to go home rather than fight to stay, the Boston cases are
being regarded as a test of aliens' rights.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service ``is saying the
government doesn't have to come up with any evidence at all,'' said
attorney Susan Akram, who is orchestrating the aliens' defense.
``The INS has never brought a shred of evidence.''
   ``It's a test of what the government burden is,'' said Akram,
head of the Political Asylum Immigration Representation Project.
``Can the government haul anybody in off the streets and deport
them if they refuse to answer questions based on their
constitutional right not to do so? This is ridiculous.''
   The defendants were among 83 Salvadoran, Mexican, Brazilian and
Cuban stablehands rounded up Oct. 21, 1988 at Suffolk Downs during
a dawn workout.
   Of the 83 people, six were found to be in the United States
lawfully. Some went home, while others admitted their illegal
status and applied for asylum.
   The rest invoked their Fifth Amendment guarantee against
self-incrimination at their deportation hearings. They want the
government to prove they are here illegally.
   That isn't happening. Instead, INS attorneys are using an
argument allowed in civil cases: that silence alone is ground for
deportation.
   Charles Wheeler, director of the National Center for Immigrants'
Rights in Los Angeles, called this development alarming.
   ``It's disturbing if the immigration judge is making an
inference from their silence that a person is an alien,'' he said.
``It reverses the whole idea that you are innocent until proven
guilty.''
   But an INS official says the government is following precedent
well-established in civil cases.
   ``The government doesn't have to do any more,'' said Michael
Creppy, acting deputy counsel for the INS in Washington. ``This is
nothing new. The law is pretty clear in this matter. To me it's
just a tactic to be able to stay here.''
   Among the 38 aliens who invoked the Fifth Amendment was
21-year-old Salvadoran. His story is typical, said Akram, who
requested the man be identified only as Jay.
   One of 10 children in a farming family, Jay is from the
mountains of El Salvador, where the army and the anti-government
guerrillas have been waging war. He said both sides terrorize the
inhabitants.
   Jay told his attorney that by age 19, he was forced to act four
times as a lookout on a guerrilla patrol. He knew better than to
object after seeing a friend's face shot off for refusing to act as
a guerrilla informant.
   Last year, Jay fled, taking a bus to Mexico. From there, he
crossed the U.S. border undetected and made his way from California
to Massachusetts.
   Two months ago, Jay had his day in Immigration Court. The
attorney for the INS questioned him about where he came from and
how he got here.
   Jay replied in Spanish, ``I refuse to answer under the
protection of the Fifth Amendment of the United States because my
answer could incriminate me.'' The INS lawyer then asked the judge
to deport him.
   Jay's case is on appeal before the Board of Immigration Appeals.
   Wheeler said the use of the Fifth Amendment in deportation cases
is rare but crucial.
   ``It's an important defense and it would be a tragic betrayal if
this was taken away from aliens,'' he said.
   The INS' Creppy said the agency feels it will win.
   ``When you weigh the public interest versus the aliens'
interest, this is a case that is clear,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891220-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-89 0917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-PanamanianReax     12-20 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panamanian Reax,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Opponents Hope For Democracy; Supporters Urge Resistance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition politicians said they
hoped the U.S. invasion of Panama would bring democracy to the
country, but supporters of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega called it
``genocide against Panama.''
   The U.S. decision to ``remove the obstacle of the dictatorship
was serious news, but we grasp it with hope,'' said Ricardo Arias
Calderon, who was sworn in as first vice president shortly after
the U.S. effort began.
   Arias, who spoke on the radio, was a vice presidential candidate
in the May 7 elections that were voided when results showed Noriega
opponents winning.
   Guillermo Endara was sworn in as president, and Guillermo Ford
was sworn in as vice president along with Arias.
   ``Tomorrow we will have the opportunity to celebrate the era of
democracy with justice and freedom,'' Endara said. He urged the
Noriega's Defense Forces, ``Don't resist, accept instead the peace
that they offer.''
   Ford said the military action ``grieves us because it involves
mourning and pain, but we pray to God that it will be the new
awakening of this nation we love so much.''
   Arias said he hoped ``with this action we can achieve the
Panamanian objectives, among them to immediately establish
democracy with full respect for the will of the people.''
   Noriega's Democratic Revolutionary Party held an emergency
meeting at an undisclosed site, said the government national radio,
broadcasting as the national resistance network.
   Carlos Duque, Noriega's presidential candidate in the May 7
elections, called on all ``nationalist parties'' to join in the
struggle.
   ``The United States has just committed the biggest error and is
going to pay for that,'' he said.
   Rigoberto Paredes, another party leader, called the U.S. action
an ``infamous invasion.'' He asked Latin American countries to tell
the United States ``to stop this genocide against Panama.''
   ``We are not going to surrender,'' he said.
   Not all those outraged by the invasion were Noriega backers.
   A woman in Diablo, just south of the U.S. Army base at Fort
Clayton, said: ``This is humiliating. I feel completely impotent.
My blood is boiling.'' She said she does not support Noriega but
also does not support the idea of a U.S. invasion.
   As she spoke, U.S. trucks passed on a nearby road and fighting
raged near Defense Forces headquarters.
   ``They are not going to enjoy it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
