<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hispanic character who used to begin
every comedy routine ``My name, Jose Jimenez'' is being resurrected
to sell cars.
   Comedian Bill Dana, who created Jose, declared the character
``dead'' in 1969 after complaints that it was an unfavorable
stereotype.
   ``Jose has become very sophisticated over the years,'' Dana
said. ``Nowadays we call him Jose Everyman.''
   Dana has signed a contract with Cardin and Cherry, the Nashville
advertising agency whose Ernest P. Worrall character has been
played into a hit by actor Jim Varney.
   Dana has kept busy over the years as an advertising executive,
actor, scriptwriter and songwriter. Last year he appeared on David
Letterman's late-night talk show and popped up as an aged priest on
an episode of ``The Golden Girls.''
   He just completed writing his second episode for ``Matlock.''
   Dana, in Nashville on Wednesday to begin filming commercials for
a local car dealer, said viewers can expect to see many changes in
Jose 25 years after ``The Bill Dana Show'' was on network
television.
   ``The only thing he kept is his wide-eyed innocence,'' Dana said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacqueline Onassis and the Wampanoag Indians are
close to settling a dispute over a strip of Martha's Vineyard
beach-front property, attorneys for both sides said.
   An agreement over the 264-foot stretch was expected to be
reached at a hearing scheduled for Feb. 2, said Paul Sulla, a
Boston attorney for the Wampanoag. Sulla said Tuesday that he could
not discuss details he said are still being worked out.
   ``There have been negotiations but we're not quite there yet,''
said Onassis attorney Brian Hurley.
   Mrs. Onassis bought a 17 percent interest in the beach property
in 1980 from one of the 25 Wampanoag Indians. Since then she has
waged a court battle over the remaining interest in the land, which
is surrounded by her private 380-acre retreat.
   She has offered a land swap and visitation rights to the areas
the Wampanoag consider sacred. But the descendants of the island's
original settlers want to keep their share of the beach because
they say it plays an important part in their heritage.
