<TEXT>
   The nation's dominant long-distance telephone
company, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., announced it will cut
basic, daytime interstate rates an average of 1.3 percent Jan. 1.
Evening rates will drop an average of 2.0 percent.
   AT&amp;T said Tuesday the lowered rates reflect reduced expenses,
mainly from reduced fees that AT&amp;T will pay in 1990 to local
telephone companies for access to local exchanges.
   AT&amp;T said the reductions were necessary under changes earlier
this year in the Federal Communications Commission's regulation of
long-distance charges. The FCC now imposes caps on AT&amp;T's
long-distance rates based on the company's long-distance expenses,
as opposed to a preset rate of return.
