<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     12-20 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined moderately today,
registering no strong reaction to the U.S. military action in
Panama.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.24 to
2,685.37 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 668 up, 755 down and 505
unchanged.
   Analysts said investors were cautiously watching the situation
in Panama, but apparently not viewing it as any cause to make big
changes in their strategies.
   They noted that the prospective economic effects of the
confrontation, if any, remained unclear.
   At the same time, brokers said, stock traders appeared to draw
only brief encouragement from an upward revision in the latest
government figures on economic growth.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product grew at
a 3.0 percent annual rate, after adjustment for inflation, in the
third quarter of the year, up from a previous estimate of 2.7
percent.
   Economists' projections remained gloomy, however, for the
results to be posted in the fourth quarter and the early stages of
1990.
   Walt Disney fell 10 to 113] in selling attributed to recession
worries and a more wary appraisal by some analysts of the company's
earnings outlook.
   Stride Rite dropped 4[ to 23[. The company said its earnings for
this year and next are likely to come in on the low side of
estimates.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dipped .10 to 189.30. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .03 at 367.92.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.29 million shares with two
hours to go.
